data.title: Croatian economy grows 3.6% year-on-year in the fourth quarter
data.description:
Croatia's economy grew 3.6% year-on-year in the fourth quarter, up from 2.3% in the previous three months, helped by stronger manufacturing output and a jump in investment, an unadjusted preliminary figure from the statistical office showed on Friday.

On a seasonally adjusted basis, Croatia's gross domestic product grew by 1.4% in the fourth quarter versus the previous three months.

data.title: Greek retail sales rise 5.1% y/y in December
data.description:
Greek retail sales by volume rose 5.1% in December compared to the same month a year earlier after a revised 0.7% rise in November, statistics service ELSTAT said on Friday.

Sales volume of the food sector was up 6.8% year-on-year, with the sales volume of the non-food sector (except automotive fuel) increasing 7.7% while the automotive fuel sector's sales volume was down 1.2% on the year, the data showed.

data.title: Diesel cash diffs hit one-month low as traders eye April discussions
data.description:
Asia's diesel markets recouped some losses on Friday, with March-April paper timespreads rebounding into a wider backwardation, while spot cash differentials fell to one-month lows.

Regional demand is still considered all right in the near term, some trade sources say, though the key driver for April will be China's spot export availability.

April spot discussions are slated to start next week, the sources added.

Meanwhile, slightly supportive for markets, the east-west price spreads were still discussed at discounts of more than $55 per metric ton.

However, freight costs did rise slightly as well, with the costs to ship around 90,000 metric tons of diesel on the Middle East-Europe route at around $51 per ton.

Refining margins (GO10SGCKMc1) traded at the lowest point this week of slightly below $22 a barrel, though such levels were still higher week-on-week.

Cash differentials (GO10-SIN-DIF) eased further to one-month lows, closing Friday's trading session at premiums of 84 cents per barrel.

On jet fuel, trading window activity remained dominated by trading house Vitol this week, though Chinese selling activity stayed brisk for March cargoes.

The Western trading major has so far bought 600,000 barrels of the aviation fuel on the trading window for March 5-15 delivery.

Regrade (JETREG10SGMc1) went back to flat levels, with jet fuel paper markets still outperforming gasoil.

SINGAPORE CASH DEALS

- One gasoil deal, no jet fuel deal

INVENTORIES

- Gasoil stocks held independently in the Amsterdam-Rotterdam-Antwerp (ARA) refining and storage hub rose around 4.2% on the week, data from Dutch consultancy Insights Global showed on Thursday.

NEWS

- The cost of hiring a supertanker from the Middle East to China exceeded $200,000 a day on Thursday for the first time since 2020 as the threat of U.S. attacks on Iran grows and buyers seek to lock in oil cargoes, according to data and market sources.

- The U.S. has slowed the sale of Russian oil giant Lukoil's international assets to use them as a bargaining chip in the Ukraine peace talks, according to four sources familiar with the discussions.

- Saudi Arabia may raise April crude prices to Asia for the first time in five months due to higher demand from India, in an effort to replace Russian supplies and soothe supply disruption fears as the threat of a U.S.-Iran military conflict grows, refining sources said.

data.title: Puma Still Needs to Show Evidence of Brand Turnaround — Market Talk
data.description: Puma is in the early stages of a significant brand revamp, Deutsche Bank analyst Adam Cochrane says in a note. "We are yet to see any evidence of a rebuild in brand heat at this stage," he says. Underlying sales trend for the German sports group should improve in the first quarter, before fading again in the second quarter, he notes. "Maybe this is enough evidence for some. We will wait," the analyst says. "We believe the shares have priced too much of a successful turnaround already," Cochrane adds. Deutsche Bank maintains its hold rating on the stock until there is more evidence of the turnaround. Shares fall 3%. (andrea.figueras@wsj.com)

data.title: French Inflation to Rise But Stay Among Eurozone's Lowest — Market Talk
data.description: French inflation rebounded in February a little more than expected, though price pressures remain moderate, ING economist Charlotte de Montpellier says in a note. Inflation was 1.1%, up from 0.4% in January, EU-harmonized data shows. Much of that rise was down to energy base effects after government-regulated gas tariffs were cut by 15% in February last year, she says. "In the coming months, a further small rise in headline inflation is likely, as energy base effects gradually become less favorable." However, with services price rises still contained, inflation should remain subdued in the months ahead, fluctuating between 1% and 1.5%, the economist says. France should continue to be among the countries with the lowest inflation rates in the eurozone, she says. (edward.frankl@wsj.com)

data.title: Italy's A2A says no decisions yet on rumoured Erg tie-up
data.description:
Italian utility A2A , reacting to reports of a possible takeover and merger with renewables group Erg , said on Friday it was exploring "strategic options" but had not taken any decisions.

"A2A regularly evaluates strategic options consistent with its business plan and holds discussions with various potential partners," it said in a statement, calling it a normal process.

The group said that several options were currently the subject of preliminary and exploratory talks and no decisions had been made. It added it would inform the public of any relevant developments.

At 1008 GMT A2A shares were flat on the Milan bourse, while Erg was up 1.7%.

data.title: ING publishes agenda and proxy materials for 2026 AGM
data.description:
ING publishes agenda and proxy materials for 2026 AGM

ING today published the agenda and proxy materials for the 2026 Annual General Meeting (AGM) to be held on Tuesday 14 April 2026.

The agenda includes the proposed appointment of Ida Lerner as Chief Financial Officer and member of the Executive Board, succeeding Tanate Phutrakul. Shareholders will also vote on updated remuneration policies for the Executive Board and Supervisory Board.

Full details of all agenda items are included in the proxy materials for our AGM. The proxy materials also include the 2025 Annual Report, including the Annual Accounts and the reports of the Executive Board and the Supervisory Board, as published on 26 February 2026, as well as other information and documents as required by law. The proxy materials, including the agenda for the AGM, are available on our website.

Registered shareholders may attend the AGM starting at 2:00pm CEST in person at Muziekgebouw aan 't IJ (Piet Heinkade 1, 1019 BR Amsterdam, the Netherlands)

The supporting materials published today provide further details on how to register, participate and vote. The AGM will also be webcast live via ing.com. Shareholders are advised to check the information on the website regularly for any updates, including details on admission requirements.

Note for editors

For more on ING, please visit www.ing.com. Frequent news updates can be found in the Newsroom. Photos of ING operations, buildings and its executives are available for download at Flickr.

ING PROFILE

ING is a global financial institution with a strong European base, offering banking services through its operating company ING bank. The purpose of ING Bank is: empowering people to stay a step ahead in life and in business. ING Bank's more than 60,000 employees offer retail and wholesale banking services to customers in over 100 countries.

ING Group shares are listed on the exchanges of Amsterdam (INGA NA, INGA.AS), Brussels and on the New York Stock Exchange (ADRs: ING US, ING.N).

ING aims to put sustainability at the heart of what we do. Our policies and actions are assessed by independent research and ratings providers, which give updates on them annually. ING's ESG rating by MSCI has been upgraded from 'AA' to 'AAA' in October 2025. As of June 2025, in Sustainalytics' view, ING's management of ESG material risk is 'Strong' with an ESG risk rating of 18.0 (low risk). ING Group shares are also included in major sustainability and ESG index products of leading providers. Here are some examples: Euronext, STOXX, Morningstar and FTSE Russell.

data.title: Boho Group Signs Final Financing Agreement with Deutsche Bank – Refinancing Successfully Completed
data.description:
Boho Group AB (publ) announces that it has signed a final financing agreement with Deutsche Bank. The previously communicated refinancing has now been fully executed and is in place.

The new financing, amounting to EUR 17.3 million, carries an interest margin of 2.25% above 12-month Euribor, corresponding to a total interest rate of approximately 4.44% at current levels, with a maturity of 15 years. This represents a substantial improvement of more than 40% compared to the Company’s previous financing costs and equates to savings of approximately SEK 6.5 million compared to last year.

The refinancing significantly strengthens Boho Group’s financial position through materially lower interest expenses, improved cash flow, and increased financial flexibility. The new structure provides a stable platform for the Company’s continued development along Marbella’s Golden Mile, including its ongoing and planned expansion projects.

“This is an important strategic milestone for Boho Group. We are materially reducing our financing costs while establishing a long-term, internationally anchored banking relationship, which is crucial for our next development phase” says Andreas Bonnier, CEO of Boho Group.

If you have any questions, please contact:

Boho Group AB (publ)

Andreas Bonnier, CEO

E-mail: andreas@bohogroup.com

Phone: +46 733 36 65 77

Website: www.bohogroup.com

About the company

Boho Group is a hotel development and operating company at the top end of design and quality, operating on the Spanish Costa del Sol. The company was founded in 2014.

Boho Group owns and operates Boho Club, a boutique resort on the Golden Mile in Marbella that is award-winning for its design and architecture. Since its launch in 2019, both the hotel and the restaurant have established themselves as a leading player in Marbella. Visit the Boho Club website, www.bohoclub.com, to book a hotel room or a table in the restaurant. The restaurant is open every day and serves breakfast, lunch and dinner.

Mangold is the Company's Certified Adviser. Mangold can be reached on telephone number 08-503 015 50 or e-mail ca@mangold.se.
